revision.text:
==English==
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|el|ξινομυζήθρα}}.
===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}
# A [[Greek]] [[cheese]] made from strained [[ewe]] or [[goat]] [[whey]] and a little [[milk]].
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Dishing: Great Dish--and Dishes--from America's Most Beloved Gossip Columnist|author=Liz Smith|passage=''Sfakiani pita'', a cheese pie of local fame, something between a crepe and a pancake. The cheese is '''''xynomyzithra''''', panfried and served with a drizzling of thyme honey.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xNqSgi0_syUC&lpg=PA234&dq=%22xynomyzithra%22&pg=PA234#v=onepage&q=%22xynomyzithra%22&f=false|year=2005}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Cheese: A Global History|page=70|author=Andrew Dalby|year=2009|passage=It is one of a group of similar traditional products linked to the same geographical region: '''''xynomyzithra''''' in Crete, ''sérac'' (variously written) in Savoy, ''brocotte'' in parts of France, ''brossat'' in Catalonia, ''requesón'' in Spain (and ''requesón'' and ''ricota'' in Latin America); similar but not identical, because Corsican ''brociu'' can be eaten fresh but can also be ripened for several months, as ''brocciu passu'', and thus develops a drier texture and stronger flavor.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dbWcda9KW2kC&lpg=PA70&dq=%22xynomyzithra%22&pg=PA70#v=onepage&q=%22xynomyzithra%22&f=false}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Greek Islands|page=251|author=Korina Miller|year=2010|passage=In the southwestern Sfakia area, the thin ''Sfakiani pita'', filled with ''myzithra'' and topped with honey, is a dessert; however, travel just a bit further west, to Paleohora, and you will find your ''myzithropitakia'' will probably be made of the sour '''''xynomyzithra''''', according to local custom.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZPlpS4zHuqQC&lpg=PA251&dq=%22xynomyzithra%22&pg=PA251#v=onepage&q=%22xynomyzithra%22&f=false}}
